Clustering - KMeans¶

Cluster finding initially seekd to find $N$ clusters in a data set and to subsequently identify which data points belong to each cluster. While there are a number of different approaches to clustering, one of the easiest to understand is the k-means algorithm.

Manhattan Distance¶

  • The taxicab distance between two vectors p,q in an n-dimensional real vector space with fixed Cartesian coordinate system, is the sum of the lengths of the projections of the line segment between the points onto the coordinate axes.
  • Sum of abs value of difference between vector p and q

Euclidean Distance¶

  • sqrt of sum of square of (difference between vector p and q)
In [56]:
x =  dataset[features2]

Scale the data -¶

  1. StandardScaler

  2. MinMaxScaler

    • Many machine learning algorithms require that features are on the same scale
    • Features may have very different variances!
    • Variance of a feature measures may spread of its values
    • In kmeans : feature variance = feature influence
    • StandardScaler transforms each feature to have mean 0 and variance 1 Standardization
    • MinMaxScaler scales each input variable separately to the range 0 1 Normalization
In [58]:
# split data into training and testing and scale using Minmax scaling
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler, StandardScaler
scaler  = StandardScaler()
scaler.fit(x) # fit the data
x_scale = scaler.transform(x) # transform the data

Find an optimum K¶

  1. From Elbow curve -

    • Distortion: It is calculated as the average of the squared distances from the cluster centers of the respective clusters. Typically, the Euclidean distance metric is used.
    • Inertia: It is the sum of squared distances of samples to their closest cluster center.
In [48]:
#Let's select the optimum number of clusters for k-means classification
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
wcss = []

for i in range(2, 7):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = i, init = 'k-means++',
                    max_iter = 100, n_init = 10, random_state = 10) # fitting my first k
    kmeans.fit(x_scale)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)
    #r-square= betweeness
    
#Plotting the results onto a line graph to observe 'The elbow'
plt.plot(range(2, 7), wcss)
plt.title('Elbow Method')
plt.xlabel('Association')# between clster sum of square
plt.ylabel('WCSS') #within cluster sum of squares
plt.show()
